<subSubSection box="[198,1139,231,258]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,151,617]" box="[198,1139,231,258]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,231,257]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Etymology:</emphasis>
Named after my son, Nuno Falqueto Vaz de Mello. Gender neutral.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,151,617]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,361,271,297]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Distribution:</emphasis>
Central, northern and northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[793,912,272,298]" name="Argentina" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, occupying about the Southern 
<collectingRegion country="Argentina" name="Chaco" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Chaco province</collectingRegion>
of the Chacoan subgregion (
<figureCitation box="[538,641,312,338]" captionStart="FIGURES 107–108" captionStartId="69.[151,269,1969,1993]" captionTargetBox="[166,1417,182,1945]" captionTargetId="figure-37@69.[166,1420,182,1945]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="FIGURES 107–108. Distribution maps. 107. Genieridium medinae (circles) and G. bordoni (triangles); 108. Nunoidium argentinum (circles), Pereiraidium almeidai (squares) and Silvinha unica (triangles)." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 108</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,151,617]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,321,351,377]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Remarks:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vaz-De-Mello" authorityYear="2008" box="[329,459,352,377]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Nunoidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[329,459,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Nunoidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vaz-De-Mello" authorityYear="2008" box="[833,981,352,377]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Genieridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[833,981,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Genieridium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, the completeness of the carina separating pronotal disc from hypomeron, vertical pygidial position, and presence of posterior pronotal bead, among other characters, will readily separate it. Apomorphies of this genus are the presence of posterior pronotal bead, absence of modification in male claws, elongation of spermatheca, and psammophilous modifications of metalegs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,151,617]" box="[198,748,551,578]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,367,551,577]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Composition:</emphasis>
Only the 
<typeStatus box="[484,534,552,578]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">type</typeStatus>
species is known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
